postcontent:
Update: So I woke up with a bunch of texts and a page of emails. Unexpected.... I am going in the order in which I received the messages so if I don't reply don't take it personally, I'm just lazy. Once the rifle is gone from my possession I will remove this post. 

I have for sale a Polish tantal. 
Mechanically everything runs flawlessly. Has the grey, non-key holing barrel, G2 internals with the spine of the hammer filed so that it does not get stuck back when slowly pulled back (meaning smoother cycling) has Krebs peep sight and a knurled round charging handle. 
Cosmetics, however, is a completely different story.. It came with a cleaning rod that was too big, so that's laying around somewhere. You can have it with the gun if you'd like, but it is useless. The wood stock is pressed in with no screws, holds just fine, but still..
The handguard is a galil style tapco Han guard that had to be filed in certain places and then pressed into place by me taking a torch to the receiver and forming the handguard into it so there are marks on the receiver and the hand guard is now a little loose after about 300 rounds heating it up (cheap plastic pos) theres also a hole in I from where I over filed it to get a comfortable grip. Easy part to swap out, but i don't have the motivation if I'm just going to sell it any way. 

The way I see it, the gun is 400, you can get new furniture and some alumihyde (or krylon if you want something that wont last) for under 100. So that makes a decent 74 for under 500. Or you can just have a rifle that functions flawlessly and looks like crap for 400. Great truck gun. 
Comes with one tapco 30rd mag and 150 rds of 5.45

title: For Sale:  Springfield Standard M1A OD Green 7.62 NATO MA9109
postcontent: From 1959 to 1970 the M14 served with distinction as the standard issue rifle of the United States military. When Springfield Armory® in Geneseo, IL made the civilian legal variant – the M1A – available to the public in 1974, shooters were finally able to enjoy the same rifle that so many servicemen had utilized in the past.  The Standard Series is a faithful semi-auto only recreation of the original M14. Keep in mind that the Standard M1A is as well suited for a day at the range as it is for filling that special place in your military collection. All the design features that the Armed Services found essential for a battle rifle make the Standard M1A a great shooter. The windage and elevation adjustable rear sight minimizes the effort required to zero the rifle. The two-stage military trigger, detachable box magazine, op-rod and roller cam bolt call to mind the rich history of the M1A while providing functional ease of operation and legendary reliability.

I am selling as a Collectable, Not as an Adult beverage

18-ounce Bat Bottles, Coors Light and Original Coors 
The first "Limited Edition" Bat Bottles were available for three months, in 1996, coming out on Opening Day of Baseball Season. The next year they had bottles with some players names but these are from First Limited Edition with no players names

The amber bottles are 11 1/2 inches tall and nearly 3 inches wide. They feature a simulated wood-grain texture that is molded directly into the glass. The Coors Light and Original Coors labels are located where a trademark would be on a real bat, on the bat's barrel section.
The bottle's neck, shaped like a bat's handle, is decorated with stripes mimicking the tape used to enhance a batter's grip. No paper labels are used on the bottles. They instead are decorated in a process known as applied ceramic labeling. Minute ceramic particles, called ceramic frit, are applied by silk-screen then oven-baked into the surface of the bottle creating a finish that looks as if it were painted.
Even the bottle's cap features a simulated wood grain along with the number 18, in this case the number of ounces of ice-cold Coors beer inside the bottle.
